<question xmlns='http://www.gradians.com'>
  <statement>
    <tex>\text{Find the integral of the function}\\
\sin ^4 x</tex>
  </statement>
  <step>
    <context>\text{The following trigonometric identity would}\\
\text{convert $\sin^ 4x$ to the more easily integrable}\\
\text{sum of sines or cosines form.}</context>
    <tex correct='true'>2\sin^2A=1-\cos 2A \text{ and }2\cos^2A=1+\cos 2A</tex>
    <tex>\sin^2 A +\cos^ 2 A=1</tex>
    <reason>\begin{align}
\sin ^4 x &amp;= \sin^2 x \cdot \sin^2 x
  =\dfrac{1}{4}(1-\cos 2x)^2 \\
&amp;= \dfrac{1}{8}(3 + \cos 4x - 4\cos 2x)
\end{align}</reason>
  </step>
  <step>
    <context>I=\int \sin ^4 xdx=\int\dfrac{1}{8}(3 + \cos 4x - 4\cos 2x)dx \\
\text{Is the following correct?}</context>
    <tex correct='true'>\begin{align}
I &amp;= \int\dfrac{1}{8}(3 + \cos 4x - 4\cos 2x)dx \\
  &amp;= \dfrac{1}{8}\left[3x + \dfrac{\sin 4x}{4}-4\dfrac{\sin 2x}{2}\right]+C\\
  &amp;= \dfrac{3x}{8}+\dfrac{1}{4}\sin 2x-\dfrac{1}{32}\sin 4x + C
\end{align}</tex>
    <tex>\begin{align}
I &amp;= \int\dfrac{1}{8}(3 + \cos 4x - 4\cos 2x)dx \\
  &amp;= \dfrac{1}{8}\left[3x + \sin 4x-4\sin 2x\right]+C\\
  &amp;= \dfrac{3x}{8}+\dfrac{1}{2}\sin 2x-\dfrac{1}{8}\sin 4x + C
\end{align}</tex>
    <reason>
\int \cos (a x)dx = \dfrac{\sin (a x)}{a}+ C \\
\text{where C is the constant of integration.}</reason>
  </step>
